course_metadata.title: Modern sustainable buildings and their structures of steel, wood and composites

content_chunks.content: The aim of this digital course is to equip students with basic understanding of the environmental implications of construction material choices, emphasizing timber, concrete, steel, and their composites. The course fosters an appreciation of wood as a renewable resource and its significance in sustainable construction. Students will develop the ability to apply lifecycle assessment (LCA) methodologies and normative frameworks to evaluate material sustainability and integrate principles of recycling and the circular economy into innovative building design solutions.

Sustainable building materials technology for environmentally conscious construction and circular economy implementation - this course delivers comprehensive expertise in evaluating and selecting timber, concrete, steel, and composite materials based on environmental impact assessment and lifecycle performance analysis. Students master lifecycle assessment (LCA) methodologies, forest carbon sequestration principles, and cross-laminated timber (CLT) technology that enable sustainable material choices. The curriculum covers material renewability evaluation, durability assessment, and circular economy integration strategies that minimize environmental impact while maximizing structural longevity. Graduates emerge skilled in implementing normative frameworks for sustainability assessment, material recycling solutions, and innovative building designs that balance performance requirements with environmental responsibility through advanced material selection and comprehensive lifecycle optimization techniques.
